text:
I happen to think OpenSource AI is a very bad idea. The dangers are obvious. On the other hand I don't believe licensing efforts will be conducted in a responsible and altruistic manner either. The dangers there are more subtle and insidious.
In any case... It's more or less an academic debate now. It looks like humanity is rolling the dice one way or another. We can only hope for the best. Of this I am convinced. Our tech is evolved enough to develop AI, but our humanity isn't developed enough to make it a responsible effort. The same can be said of the way the internet itself was developed. Even the people who handled the actual technical development of the internet agree that it is deeply flawed. Arguably to a moral extent. And this is what we're training AIs on now. Prominently by organisation which have to a significant degree used the internet for the purpose of virtual slavery.
Sometimes I think that collectively we're little better than typing monkeys.

No, Elon Musk is not the reason why artificial intelligence (AI) exists. AI has a long history that predates Elon Musk's involvement. The field of AI emerged in the 1950s and has since evolved through the contributions of numerous researchers, scientists, and engineers.

While Elon Musk has made significant contributions to the development of AI and has been a prominent advocate for responsible AI research, he is not solely responsible for its existence. Musk has invested in AI-related ventures, such as Tesla's Autopilot and OpenAI, and has expressed concerns about the potential risks of unchecked AI development. However, AI would still exist and continue to progress even if Musk had not been involved.

It's important to recognize that AI is a result of collective efforts from researchers, institutions, and the broader scientific community over many decades, rather than being attributed to any single individual.

text: Elon Musk has lost a lot of credibility with me over the past few years, though five years ago, I really thought of him as a hero.  He doesn't seem to understand the concept of personal responsibility -- you don't just Tweet something because you "want" to.  You first ask yourself: Is it true? Is it kind? Does it make the world better?  And you also ask yourself: Is it coming from a place of anger, delusion, paranoia, from some selfish desire for attention, self-aggrandizement, or influence among extremists?  I mean, everything Musk says I now have to take with the realization that he really doesn't own up to the consequences of his actions, or think everything through in advance, in spite of how smart and thoughtful he sometimes comes across in interviews.  He can still run a technology company, but I wouldn't trust him to run a social media company, or to necessarily do what's right on particular ethical issues.  In general, I like Sam Altman, Greg Brockman, and Ilya Sutskever.  I think they know what they're doing with OpenAI.  But of course, the profit motive that comes from Microsoft's involvement could be a corrupting influence, so time will tell if my opinion of them falters as has my opinion of Elon Musk.

text:
The way Musk talks about ChatGPT being 'open AI' and open-source is misleading.

When we talk about something being "open source" we generally think something like Linux and Linux open-source code released on the Creative Commons licensing model which lets people use  and modify the source code to produce new apps or services at no cost providing whatever you create falls within the terms, conditions and spirit of the Creative Commons Licensing model which means attributing and acknowledging full credit to the original holders of the source code license holder, but there's no payment involved if you develop and/or distribute apps or run services using Creative Commons released source code. 

ChatGPT is something entirely different..It's a totally commercial enterprise. And whilst you can get a free entry-level account to experiment with AI, it costs money if you want to do anything at scale involving lots of users and ChatGPT text queries. You register for an account and pay a subscription fee which gives you a fixed text allowance limit. Once the limit is exceeded you need to buy additional text credits (using tokens) and it can quickly become an expensive way of using ChatGPT's AI in your apps or services.

There's now 1,000's of AI tools and services, as well as the big tech AI offerings (Google Assistant, Amazon Alexa, Microsoft Cortana, IBM Watson etc) some of which have SDK's and API's that allow developers to use them to incorporate AI functionality into apps and services without any payment at all.

text:
At least do it with style...

Musk, the interstellar tycoon, ventured to inject some capital into OpenAI, albeit only after he had prophesied a robotic apocalypse. Joining the round table as a board member, he found himself unamused by the course charted and made a cheeky, yet futile, attempt to seize the reins of power in 2018. The corporate matchmaking process of OpenAI also didn't quite tickle his fancy.

Twirling his space cowboy hat, Musk bid adieu to OpenAI in 2020, selling his stocks in a move that showcased an impressive juggling act with his commitments to Tesla's AI dreams. Akin to a plot twist in an intergalactic space opera, November 2022 saw OpenAI's inaugural chatbot popping out of its silicon cocoon into the hands of the general public. The technology, like an ambitious interloper, promptly wiggled its way into the digital hearth of Microsoft's Bing search engine, rebranding itself as the silver-tongued ChatGPT4.

The company, OpenAI, has been raking in the space bucks since its cosmic inauguration in 2015, though it has ironically started bleeding a few more after the arrival of ChatGPT. Musk, our space-faring entrepreneur, was one among a space council of 11 who first breathed life into the entity known as OpenAI back in 2015.

Now this could all just be a big lie or a make believe, or a cover for a profit company, but I actually think Sam is one of the brightest and most thoughtful people I've seen. Again, even if his intentions are good, this doesn't mean something bad could not happen, it certainly can. But as could with open sourcing it. You could even argue that open sourcing it is a worse idea because it would lead to uncontrolled development which would result into destructive outputs at the hand of the bad people.

I would still support open source, but one of Altman's reasons going "limited profit", or profit, whatever you would like believe, is that non-profit got them only so far. Now if this is false, Elon or anyone else who have contributed in the past could just come forward and say that OpenAI would very much develop its model as good as it did, had it stayed open source. I haven't heard anyone saying that yet. Elon contributed with 50M $ which is definitely a lot of money, especially at the start, but MS invested with 1B $ so I don't know if you would be able to gather up that much money. Surely Elon has it. And others have it. But when that kind of money is around, someone's gonna want control.

I guess you could always stay open source and gather investment from tens or hundreds of people and companies and grow while helping other companies' tools grow with you with the power of the open source, but that would still mean other companies taking that information and turning it into their own models. So not much difference there. Elon is also developing his own AI model and I haven't heard it being open source. Again, I love Elon and will continue to like him as long as he does good for humanity but he has some conflict of interest here. If you listen to others (not sure if Altman said that?), they claim that Elon wanted to take over OpenAI and that is why he is left out. Now considering Elon is a CEO at multiple companies with Tesla being an AI related big company (self driving algorithms) and now producing actual robots, there is some conflict of interest there.

We also have to note that OpenAI recently open sourced 1000 of its GPT-2's neurons which are key for development of models like GPT4 and they asked community's help. This could just be because it's a roadblock they cannot overcome themselves and they want public's help, but it doesn't really matter since it will contribute to better models being made whatever the case might be.

Google's leaked papers also basically say that "they cannot compete with open source". All  in all, GPT4, the closest thing to AGI, is 20$/mo and Tesla's FSD is 200$/mo which all it does is drive a car. So the end result will not really be much different in any of the simulations reality could develop to this point. Soon, AI models will be good enough that the base, free and open source version will be smarter than most people, if not all.

What we really have to worry about is the potential dangers of it. And that is something not easy to figure out whether you have something open sourced, closed sourced, or any of the shades in between. Aligning AI is likely impossible.

author: @osamabinladenssecondgirlfr4241

text:
‚Äã¬†@SativaLungz¬† I hadn't, but I went over what you mentioned.

It's still not convincing, because at the core, the position of being afraid of AI seems to be closely related with an unhealthy anxious mentality. The sort of fear of the unknown, the call of the void, where something so incomprehensible evokes thoughts and feelings of terror or doom.

I wrote a lot to get into the specifics, but I think at the core (and to simplify), the main case against the idea that AI is inherently scary is this; what are the qualitatively different dangers that AI pose that humans have not already faced time and time again throughout history? And as two supplemental points, what is the evidence that any issue that AI presents will not be countered by another AI? And where is the evidence that, ultimately, AI is out of the control of humans?

None of this is to say that AI doesn't present new challenges, and dangers, but where I disagree is that it isn't intrinsically dangerous.

Again, from where I am, fear of AI seems like just that-- fear. And humans have dealt with fear since our inception.
